<li id="cite_note-28"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-28">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Winik, p. 197; Eicher, <i>The Longest Night</i>, p. 821, states 26,765 captured Confederates were paroled at Appomattox Court House. Calkins, p. 187, states 1,559 cavalrymen turned in their weapons on April 10, on p. 188, 2,576 artillerymen surrendered on April 11, and, on p. 192, 23,512 infantry surrendered on April 12, for a total of 27,647.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-Longstreet-29"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Longstreet_29-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Longstreet, p. 631; Lee and staff 15; Longstreet’s corps 14,833 (including 5000 attached from <a href="/wiki/A.P._Hill" class="mw-redirect" title="A.P. Hill">A.P. Hill</a>’s Third Corps (Hill died a few days earlier at Petersburg) and others who joined from Sailor’s Creek); Gordon’s corps 7,200 (including 5,200 from units dispersed at Petersburg who joined the retreat); Ewell’s corps 237; Cavalry corps 1768; Artillery 2,586; Detachments 1,649; for a total of 28,356.</span>
</li>
